rs14= 2015    | caps14= 1 | goals14= 2 | clubs14= [[FC Levadia II Tallinn|Levadia II]]\n| years15= 2016     | caps15= 12 | goals15= 2 | clubs15= [[Sein\u00e4joen Jalkapallokerho|SJK]]\n| years16= 2016\u20132017| caps16= 25 | goals16= 3 | clubs16= [[Mez\u0151k\u00f6vesdi SE|Mez\u0151k\u00f6vesd]]\n| years17= 2017 | caps17= 14| goals17= 3| clubs17= [[FC Levadia Tallinn|Levadia]]\n| club-update         = 3 June 2018\n| nationalyears1 = <!-- 1999\u2013? --> | nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 =  0 | nationalteam1 = [[Estonia national under-15 football team|Estonia U15]]\n| nationalyears2 =       | nationalcaps2 =  1 | nationalgoals2 =  0 | nationalteam2 = [[Estonia national under-18 football team|Estonia U18]]\n| nationalyears3 =       | nationalcaps3 =  6 | nationalgoals3 =  1 | nationalteam3 = [[Estonia national under-19 football team|Estonia U19]]\n| nationalyears4 =       | nationalcaps4 =  5 | nationalgoals4 =  0 | nationalteam4 = [[Estonia national under-21 football team|Estonia U21]]\n| nationalyears5 = 2004\u20132014 | nationalcaps5 = 82 | nationalgoals5 =  6 | nationalteam5 = [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]]\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Tarmo Kink''' (born 6 October 1985) is an Estonian [[association football|footballer]] who most recently played as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for Estonian [[Meistriliiga]] club [[FC Levadia Tallinn|Levadia]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nIn 2001, Kink started his career with [[SC Real Tallinn|S.C. Real]], scoring 46 goals in 15 games. In 2001, Kink spent a short loan spell with [[FC Viimsi|Viimsi]]. He scored 31 goals in just 6 games, including 9 goals in a single match against [[JK Sillam\u00e4e Kalev|Sillam\u00e4e Kalev]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neljas.ee/est/?news=911930&category=3&Nahtamatu-Tarmo-Kink |title=N\u00e4htamatu Tarmo Kink |trans-title=Invisible Tarmo Kink |author=Indrek Schwede |date=1 April 2003 |publisher=Neljas |accessdate=24 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720131103/http://www.neljas.ee/est/?news=911930&category=3&Nahtamatu-Tarmo-Kink |archivedate=20 July 2011  }}</ref> He spent the [[2002 Meistriliiga]] season on loan at the [[Meistriliiga]] club [[JK Narva Trans|Narva Trans]], where he made 24 appearances, mostly as a substitute.\n\n===Spartak Moscow===\nIn 2003, at the age of 17, Kink signed a five-year contract with the [[Russian Premier League]] club [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.postimees.ee/300304/esileht/sport/130304.php|title=Vutikoondis toob P\u00f5hja-Iirimaa vastu andekad tulevikutegijad|website=[[Postimees]]}}</ref> Kink made his debut for Spartak Moscow on 6 February 2003, against [[Shchyolkovo]] in a friendly match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccernet.ee/news.php?id=3175|title=Tarmo Kink deb\u00fcteeris Spartakis \u2013 Soccernet.ee|website=soccernet.ee}}</ref> He played his first Russian Premier League match on 23 August 2003, in a 2\u20130 defeat against [[FC Rubin Kazan|Rubin Kazan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccernet.ee/news.php?id=4562|title=Kink tegi Spartaki eest liigadeb\u00fc\u00fcdi \u2013 Soccernet.ee|website=soccernet.ee}}</ref> Kink mostly played for Spartak Moscow's reserves in Russia, although he did make two league appearances, as well as coming on as a substitute in a [[UEFA Cup]] third round defeat to [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]. In 2006, after failing to break into the first team, Kink returned to Estonia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.postimees.ee/070706/esileht/sport/196301.php|title=Tarmo Kinki m\u00e4ngud Moskva Spartakis m\u00e4ngitud|website=[[Postimees]]}}</ref>\n\n===Levadia===\nOn 6 July 2006, Kink signed a two-year contract with [[Meistriliiga]] club [[FC Levadia Tallinn|Levadia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sport.postimees.ee/1559245/tarmo-kink-siirdus-moskva-spartakist-fc-levadiasse|title=Tarmo Kink siirdus Moskva Spartakist FC Levadiasse|date=6 July 2006|website=[[Postimees]]}}</ref> Three days later, Kink played his first Meistriliiga game for Levadia in a derby against [[FC Flora Tallinn|Flora]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.postimees.ee/100706/esileht/sport/208791.php|title=Vassiljevi kaugl\u00f6\u00f6k t\u00f5i Levadiale olulise v\u00f5idu|website=[[Postimees]]}}</ref> He scored his first Meistriliiga goal for Levadia on 23 July 2006, in a 3\u20131 victory over [[FC TVMK Tallinn|TVMK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.postimees.ee/240706/esileht/sport/210417.php|title=Kink avas Levadia eest v\u00e4ravaarve|website=[[Postimees]]}}</ref> On 8 March 2008, Kink extended his current contract with Levadia until 30 November 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fclevadia.ee/dyna/site/2267est.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430030628/http://www.fclevadia.ee/dyna/site/2267est.html|url-status=dead|title=Tarmo Kink ja Deniss Malov pikendasid t\u00f6\u00f6lepinguid \u2013 FC Levadia|archivedate=30 April 2008}}</ref> On 28 July 2008, he was close to signing a three-year contract with [[Romania]]n [[Liga I]] club [[FC Gloria Buz\u0103u|Gloria Buz\u0103u]] for a fee of \u20ac200,000, but rejected the offer, because he didn't find the conditions in Romania suitable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccernet.ee/news.php?id=20939|title=Kink siiski Gloriasse ei siirdunud \u2013 Soccernet.ee|website=soccernet.ee}}</ref> On 29 July 2008, it was reported that Kink would go on trial to [[Netherlands|Dutch]] club [[De Graafschap]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccernet.ee/news.php?id=20947|title=Kink s\u00f5idab Hollandisse testimisele \u2013 Soccernet.ee|website=soccernet.ee}}</ref> However he did not get a chance to impress, picking up a knee injury just five minutes into his first training session with the club and returned to Estonia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccernet.ee/news.php?id=20986|title=Vigastus l\u00f5petas Kingi testimise \u2013 Soccernet.ee|website=soccernet.ee}}</ref>\n\n===Gy\u0151r===\nIn January 2009, Kink signed a three-and-a-half-year contract with Hungarian side [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151r]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sport.ohtuleht.ee/310492/tarmo-kink-ja-tihhon-sisov-ungarisse|title=Tarmo Kink ja Tihhon \u0160i\u0161ov Ungarisse|website=[[\u00d5htuleht]]}}</ref> He scored 3 goals in 12 matches in his first season in Hungary. Kink finished the [[2009\u201310 Nemzeti Bajnoks\u00e1g I]] as the club's top scorer with 12 goals from 28 matches. He also scored 3 goals in 2 matches against Slovakian side [[FC Nitra|Nitra]] in the qualifying phase of the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League]].\n\n===Middlesbrough===\nOn 27 July 2010, Kink signed a three-year contract with English [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] for a reported transfer fee of \u00a3850,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.estonianfreepress.com/2010/07/tarmo-kink-is-a-middlesbrough-player/|title=Tarmo Kink is a Middlesbrough Player! \u2013 Estonian Free Press|website=estonianfreepress.com}}</ref> Kink made his debut on 7 August 2010, replacing [[Justin Hoyte]] on the 60th minute of the 1\u20133 league defeat to [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]]. Kink scored his first goal on 14 September 2010, against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]], coming off the bench in the 75th minute.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_1/8989491.stm |title=Middlesbrough 2\u20131 Burnley |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=15 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/match_report/0,19764,11065_3286150,00.html |title=Tarmo double lifts Boro |publisher=Sky Sports |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=15 September 2010}}</ref> His second goal followed in the 94th minute from a 30-yard freekick smashed into the top left corner; the game finished 2\u20131 to Middlesbrough. On 6 November 2010, he scored in his club's 2\u20131 win over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_div_1/9155143.stm | work=BBC News | title=Middlesbrough 2\u20131 Crystal Palace | date=6 November 2010}}</ref> After a few months without playing, Kink was chosen to play against Ipswich Town. After that he made several substitute appearances, including one against [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] on 25 April, in which he scored a 92nd-minute winner. Throughout the 2011\u201312 season, Kink struggled for first team football. In February 2012, Kink and Middlesbrough decided to terminate his contract, making him a free agent.\n\n===Karpaty Lviv===\nIn February 2012, Kink signed a contract with Ukrainian side [[FC Karpaty Lviv|Karpaty Lviv]], which was supposed to last until the end of the season in May, but was terminated in April 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.postimees.ee/754212/tarmo-kingist-saab-sergei-zenjovi-klubikaaslane|title=Tarmo Kingist saab Sergei Zenjovi klubikaaslane|publisher=[[Postimees]]|date=28 February 2012|accessdate=6 March 2012|language=Estonian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohtuleht.ee/474112|title=FOTOD: Tarmo Kink lahkus Lvovi Karpat\u00f5st|website=[[\u00d5htuleht]]}}</ref>\n\n===Varese===\nOn August 2012, Kink signed with Italian [[Serie B]] club [[A.S. Varese 1910|Varese]].\n\n===Return to Gy\u0151r===\nIn January 2013, Kink returned to [[Gy\u0151ri ETO FC|Gy\u0151r]] on a one-year loan spell from Varese in search of more playing time.\n\n===Inverness Caledonian Thistle===\nIn March 2015, Kink signed for [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle FC|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/sport/football/inverness-caledonian-thistle/508161/inverness-caley-thistle-sign-estonian-international-tarmo-kink/|title=Inverness Caley Thistle sign Estonian international Tarmo Kink|publisher=Press & Journal|date=2 March 2015|accessdate=2 March 2015}}</ref> He made his debut later that month, coming on as a substitute in a [[Scottish Cup]] game against [[Raith Rovers F.C.|Raith Rovers]]. He made his league debut coming off the bench in a match against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31882937 |title=Partick Thistle 1&ndash;0 Inverness CT |first=Colin |last=Moffat |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=21 March 2015 |accessdate=22 March 2015}}</ref> Kink was an unused substitute in the [[2015 Scottish Cup Final]] Inverness won.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32728510 |title=Inverness CT 2&ndash;1 Falkirk |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=30 May 2015 |accessdate=4 June 2015 |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Levadia (2015)===\nOn 8 July 2015, Kink returned to his former club Levadia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tarmo Kink liitus Levadiaga|language=Estonian|date=8 July 2015|publisher=Soccernet|url=http://www.soccernet.ee/tarmo-kink-liitus-levadiaga}}</ref>\n\n===SJK===\nIn January 2016, Kink signed a contract with Finnish champion side [[Sein\u00e4joen Jalkapallokerho|SJK]] for the 2016 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kink signs for SJK|url=http://www.sjk2007.fi/uutiset/Viron_maajoukkueen_Tarmo_Kink_siirtyy_SJK_paitaan_8606.html|website=Official SJK page}}</ref>\n\n===Mez\u0151k\u00f6vesd===\nIn July 2016, Kink left SJK and signed for Hungarian club [[Mez\u0151k\u00f6vesdi SE|Mez\u0151k\u00f6vesd]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ametlik: Kink s\u00f5lmis Ungari k\u00f5rgliigasse t\u00f5usnud klubiga lepingu|url=http://soccernet.ee/artikkel/ametlik-kink-solmis-ungari-korgliigasse-tousnud-klubiga-lepingu|website=Soccernet.ee|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Levadia (2017)===\nOn 9 August 2017, Kink once again rejoined his former club [[FC Levadia Tallinn|Levadia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Vana kahur tagasi Eestis: Tarmo Kink taasliitub Levadiaga|url=http://sport.delfi.ee/news/jalgpall/eesti/vana-kahur-tagasi-eestis-tarmo-kink-taasliitub-levadiaga?id=79135858|website=Delfi|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref> After the season end in autumn, when Levadia merged with [[FCI Tallinn|FCI]], he left the club and had an operation in December, being free agent since.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tarmo Kink: Eesti jalgpallis napib professionaalsust|url=https://sport.postimees.ee/4470279/tarmo-kink-eesti-jalgpallis-napib-professionaalsust|website=Postimees|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nKink made his [[Estonia national football team]] debut on 31 March 2004 against [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] in a friendly match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postimees.ee/010404/esileht/130525.php|title=Jalgpallurid valmistasid f\u00e4nnidele pettumuse|website=[[Postimees]]}}</ref> He scored his first national team goal from a penalty on 27 May 2008, in a 1\u20131 draw against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccernet.ee/news.php?id=19986|title=Koondiseaasta j\u00e4tkus 1:1 viigiga Gruusia vastu \u2013 Soccernet.ee|website=soccernet.ee}}</ref> Eight days later Kink scored his second goal for Estonia against [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] in another friendly match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sport.ohtuleht.ee/282216/eesti-jalgpallikoondis-voitis-faari-saared-43|title=Eesti jalgpallikoondis v\u00f5itis F\u00e4\u00e4ri saared 4:3|website=[[\u00d5htuleht]]}}</ref>\nOn 8 October 2010, Kink scored from a beautiful long range effort in a [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying]] match against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]], equalizing the game at 1\u20131 in the 63rd minute as Estonia went on to win 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://jalgpall.ee/protocol.php?st=style_fp.css&nteam_id=1&proto=431 |title=Serbia \u2013 Eesti protokoll |trans-title=Serbia \u2013 Estonia protocol |language=Estonian |publisher=[[Eesti Jalgpalli Liit]] |accessdate=22 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jalgpall.ee/news.php?st=style_fp.css&news_id=726|title=K\u00f5ik Eesti internatsionaalid|publisher=[[Estonian Football Association]]|accessdate=2 June 2012|language=Estonian|trans-title=All Estonian internationals}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|31 May 2017.}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA#Club|Europe]]\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[SC Real Tallinn|S.C. Real]]\n|[[2001 II liiga|2001]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[II liiga]]\n|9||30|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014|| || ||9||30\n|-\n|[[2003 II liiga|2003]]\n|6||16|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014|| || ||6||16\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!15!!46!! !! !!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!! !! !!15!!46\n|-\n|[[FC Viimsi|Viimsi]] (loan)\n|[[2002 III liiga|2002]]\n|[[III liiga]]\n|6||31|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014|| || ||6||31\n|-\n|[[JK Narva Trans|Narva Trans]] (loan)\n|[[2002 Meistriliiga|2002]]\n|[[Meistriliiga]]\n|24||4|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014|| || ||24||4\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moscow]]\n|[[2003 Russian Premier League|2003]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Russian Premier League]]\n|2||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0|| || ||2||0\n|-\n|[[2004 Russian Premier League|2004]]\n|0||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||3||0|| || ||3||0\n|-\n|[[2005 Russian Premier League|2005]]\n|0||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014|| || ||0||0\n|-\n|[[2006 Russian Premier League|2006]]\n|0||0|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014|| || ||0||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!2!!0!! !! !!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!3!!0!! !! !!5!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[FC Levadia Tallinn|Levadia]]\n|[[2006 Meistriliiga|2006]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Meistriliiga]]\n|16||3|| || ||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||6||0||0||0||22||3\n|-\n|[[2007 Meistril