oric_tex_cities.html |title=Historical Maps of Texas Cities: Fort Worth |work= [[Perry\u2013Casta\u00f1eda Library Map Collection]] |publisher=University of Texas at Austin }}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.texasarchive.org/library/index.php/Category:Fort_Worth |work=[[Texas Archive of the Moving Image]] |location=Austin, TX |title= Fort Worth }}\n\n{{Fort Worth, Texas}}\n{{Texas year nav}}\n{{Texas History Navbox}}\n\n[[Category:History of Fort Worth, Texas| ]]\n[[Category:Timelines of cities in Texas|fort worth]]\n", "text_old": "The following is a timeline of the [[History of Fort Worth, Texas|history]] of the city of [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]], [[Texas]], United States.\n{{Dynamic list}}\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Prior to 20th century==\n{{Texas History}}\n* 1843 \u2013 The [[Treaty of Bird's Fort]] between the Republic of Texas and several Indian tribes was signed at Bird's Fort in present-day [[Haltom City, Texas]].  Article XI of the treaty provided that no one may \"pass the line of trading houses\" (at the border of the Indians' territory) without permission of the President of Texas, and may not reside or remain in the Indians' territory. In November, these \"trading houses\" were established at the junction of the Clear Fork and West Fork of the Trinity River in present-day Fort Worth.<ref name=\"books.google.com\">{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T0q_bI8_gbAC&pg=PA22&lpg=PA22 | title=Fort Worth: A Frontier Triumph| isbn=9780875655260| last1=Garrett| first1=Julia Kathryn| date=2013-05-31}}</ref>\n* 1849 \u2013 US Army [[Department of Texas]]'s \"Camp Worth\" was founded at the junction of the Clear Fork and West Fork as the northernmost of a system of forts for protecting the [[Western Frontier|American Frontier]] following the end of the [[Mexican\u2013American War]].<ref name=\"books.google.com\" /><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.texasbeyondhistory.net/forts/military.html |title = Frontier Forts}}</ref><ref name=wpa1940-chronology>{{Citation |author=Federal Writers' Project |location=New York |publisher=Hastings House |series=[[American Guide Series]] |title=Texas: A Guide to the Lone Star State |year=1940 |chapter=Chronology |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/texasguidetolone00writrich#page/670/mode/2up |via=Internet Archive|author-link=Federal Writers' Project }}</ref>\n* 1855 \u2013 Masonic Hall built.{{sfn|Talbert|1956}}\n* 1856 \u2013 Fort Worth became seat of [[Tarrant County]].{{sfn|Talbert|1956}}\n* 1873\n** Fort Worth incorporated.{{sfn|Federal Writers' Project|1940|ps=: \"Fort Worth\"}}\n** [[Fort Worth Fire Department]] established.<ref name=FWL-facts />\n* 1874 \u2013 [[Dallas]]-Fort Worth telegraph began operating.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n* 1876 \u2013 [[Texas and Pacific Railway]] began operating.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n* 1882 \u2013 Public school established.{{sfn|Talbert|1956}}\n* 1883 \u2013 First National Bank of Fort Worth established.<ref name=FWL-archival />\n* 1888 \u2013 [[Fort Worth Cats]] baseball team formed.\n* 1889\n** [[Texas Spring Palace]] (\"hall built of grain\") opened.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n** New Trinity Cemetery established.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n* 1890\n** [[Fort Worth Stockyards|Fort Worth Union Stockyards]] began operating.\n** [[Texas Wesleyan University|Polytechnic College]] founded.{{sfn|Federal Writers' Project|1940|ps=: \"Fort Worth\"}}\n* 1895 \u2013 [[Tarrant County Courthouse]] built.\n* 1896 \u2013 [[Southwestern Exposition and Livestock Show|Fort Worth Fat Stock Show]] (livestock exhibit) began.\n* 1898 \u2013 Bohemian literary club formed.<ref name=FWL-digital>{{cite web |url=http://cdm16084.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/|title=Fort Worth Library Digital Archives |publisher=City of Fort Worth |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==20th century==\n* 1901 \u2013 [[Fort Worth Library|Carnegie Public Library]] opened.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fortworthtexas.gov/library/info/default.aspx?id=5610 |title=History of the Fort Worth Library (timeline) |publisher=City of Fort Worth |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |chapter=Historical Sketches of Texas Libraries: Fort Worth |title=Handbook of Texas Libraries |number=1 |publisher=Texas Library Association |location=Austin |year=1904 |hdl=2027/uc1.b4221835 }}</ref>\n* 1903 \u2013 [[Armour and Company|Armour]] and [[Swift & Company|Swift]] meatpacking plants began operating.{{sfn|Rich|2014}}\n* 1907\n** Young Women's Christian Association established.<ref name=FWL-archival />\n** [[Fort Worth Fire Department|Fire Station]] #1 built.<ref name=FWL-facts />\n* 1908 \u2013 [[Cowtown Coliseum]] built.\n* 1909\n** \"Fire destroys 20 blocks in Fort Worth.\"<ref name=wpa1940-chronology />\n** ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]'' newspaper in publication.<ref name=LOC>{{cite web |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/search/titles/results/?city=Fort%20Worth&rows=50&state=Texas&page=1&sort=date |title=US Newspaper Directory |location=Washington DC |work=Chronicling America |publisher=Library of Congress |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n** [[Fort Worth Zoo]]<ref name=\"Kisling2001\">{{cite book|editor=Vernon N. Kisling, Jr. |title=Zoo and Aquarium History|year=2001|publisher=[[CRC Press]] |location=USA |isbn=978-1-4200-3924-5 |chapter=Zoological Gardens of the United States (chronological list) |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=ulbMBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA375 }}</ref> and [[Greenwood Memorial Park (Fort Worth)|Greenwood Memorial Park]] (cemetery) established.\n* 1910\n** [[Texas Christian University]] relocated to city.{{sfn|Federal Writers' Project|1940|ps=: \"Fort Worth\"}}\n** [[1910 United States Census#City rankings|Population]]: 73,312.<ref name=census1998 />\n* 1912\n** Oil discovered in vicinity of Fort Worth (at [[Burkburnett, Texas|Burkburnett]]).{{sfn|Federal Writers' Project|1940|ps=: \"Fort Worth\"}}\n** Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary opened.{{sfn|Federal Writers' Project|1940|ps=: \"Fort Worth\"}}\n* 1914 \u2013 [[Lake Worth (Texas)|Lake Worth]] (reservoir) and [[Allen Chapel AME Church (Fort Worth, Texas)|Allen Chapel AME Church]] built.\n* 1920 \u2013 [[1920 United States Census#City rankings|Population]]: 106,482.<ref name=census1998 />\n* 1922\n** Niles City became part of Fort Worth.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n** KFJZ and WBAP [[List of radio stations in Texas|radio]] began broadcasting.<ref name=Alicoate1939>{{citation |title=Radio Annual |oclc=2459636 |year=1939 |editor=Jack Alicoate |publisher=Radio Daily |location=New York |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/radioannual193900radi#page/378/mode/2up |chapter=Standard Broadcasting Stations of the United States: Texas }}</ref>\n* 1926 \u2013 [[F. W. Woolworth Building (Fort Worth, Texas)|Woolworth Building]] constructed.\n* 1927 \u2013 KTAT [[List of radio stations in Texas|radio]] began broadcasting.<ref name=Alicoate1939 />\n* 1929 \u2013 [[Blackstone Hotel (Fort Worth, Texas)|Blackstone Hotel]] built.<ref name=FWL-facts>{{cite web |url=http://fortworthtexas.gov/library/info/default.aspx?id=24852#Local |title=Fort Worth History Fugitive Facts (database) |author=Fort Worth Library |publisher=City of Fort Worth |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n* 1930\n** [[T&P Station|Texas & Pacific Railroad Passenger Station]] and Z Boaz municipal golf course<ref>{{citation |work=Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303552104577440453608650974 |title=Saying Goodbye to the Local Muni |date=June 1, 2012 }}</ref> opened.\n** [[1930 United States Census#City rankings|Population]]: 163,447.<ref name=census1998 />\n* 1933\n** [[Fort Worth Botanic Garden]] established.<ref name=botanic>{{cite web |url=http://www.bgci.org/garden_search.php?action=Find&ftrCountry=US&ftrKeyword=%22texas%22&x=0&y=0 |title=Garden Search: United States of America: Texas |publisher=[[Botanic Gardens Conservation International]] |location=London |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n** US Post Office built.{{sfn|Federal Writers' Project|1940|ps=: \"Fort Worth\"}}\n* 1934 \u2013 [[Texas Wesleyan University|Texas Wesleyan College]] established.\n* 1936 \u2013 US mental health hospital/farm opened on outskirts of city.{{sfn|Federal Writers' Project|1940|ps=: \"Fort Worth\"}}<ref name=FWL-facts />\n* 1939 \u2013 City Hall built.{{sfn|Federal Writers' Project|1940|ps=: \"Fort Worth\"}}\n* 1940\n** ''Lake Como Weekly'' newspaper began publication.<ref name=FWL-digital />\n** [[1940 United States Census#City rankings|Population]]: 177,662.<ref name=census1998 />\n* 1942 \u2013 US Army [[Naval Air Station Joint Reserve Base Fort Worth|Tarrant Field]] and [[Consolidated Vultee]] Aircraft plant{{sfn|Melosi|1983}} began operating.\n* 1945 \u2013 [[Fort Worth Museum of Science and History|Fort Worth Children's Museum]] opened.\n* 1946 \u2013 [[Fort Worth Opera|Fort Worth Civic Opera Association]] and All Saints' Episcopal Church congregation established.<ref name=FWL-archival />\n* 1948\n** WBAP-TV ([[List of television stations in Texas|television]]) began broadcasting.<ref name=Alicoate1960>{{citation |title=Radio Annual and Television Year Book |oclc=10512206 |year=1960 |editor=Charles A. Alicoate |publisher=Radio Daily Corp. |location=New York |chapter=Television Stations: Texas |chapterurl=https://archive.org/stream/radio00radi#page/849/mode/2up }}</ref>\n** Tarrant County Historical Society established.<ref name=FWL-archival>{{cite web |url=http://fortworthtexas.gov/library/info/default.aspx?id=5586 |title=Archival Collection |author=Fort Worth Library |publisher=City of Fort Worth |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n* 1950\n** Cowtown Drive-In cinema opened.<ref name=cinema>{{cite web |url=http://cinematreasures.org/theaters/united-states/texas/fort-worth?status=all |title=Movie Theaters in Fort Worth, TX |work=CinemaTreasures.org |publisher=Cinema Treasures LLC |location=Los Angeles |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n** [[1950 United States Census#City rankings|Population]]: 278,778.<ref name=census1998 />\n* 1954 \u2013 Fort Worth Art Museum opened.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n* 1955 \u2013 KFJZ-TV ([[List of television stations in Texas|television]]) began broadcasting.<ref name=Alicoate1960 />\n* 1957 \u2013 [[Dallas-Fort Worth Turnpike]] and [[American Airlines]] Stewardess College<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aaconferencecenter.com/about-us/property-history/ |title=Property History |work=American Airlines Training & Conference Center |publisher=[[Wyndham Hotels & Resorts|Dolce Hotels and Resorts]] |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref> opened.\n* 1958 \u2013 [[Casa Ma\u00f1ana]] theatre rebuilt.<ref name=FWL-archival />\n* 1960 \u2013 [[1960 United States Census#City rankings|Population]]: 356,268.<ref name=census1998 />\n* 1961 \u2013 [[Amon Carter Museum of American Art]] opened.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n* 1962\n** [[Van Cliburn International Piano Competition]] began.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n** [[Miss Texas Pageant]] (beauty contest) relocated to city.<ref name=FWL-archival />\n* 1964 \u2013 Fort Worth Civil Liberties Union formed.<ref name=taro>{{cite web |url=http://www.lib.utexas.edu/taro/advsearch.php?hitsPerPage=25&lang=en&query1=Fort%20Worth+%28Tex.%29&query2=dc_subject%3A&query3=|title=Fort Worth (Tex). |work=Texas Archival Resources Online |author=University of Texas Libraries |publisher=University of Texas at Austin |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n* 1968 \u2013 [[Fort Worth Museum of Science and History]] active.\n* 1969\n** Alleged [[Lake Worth Monster]] spotted.\n** Historic Fort Worth nonprofit established.<ref name=aaslh2002>{{cite book |title=Directory of Historical Organizations in the United States and Canada |year=2002 |edition=15th |isbn=0-7591-0002-0 |author=American Association for State and Local History |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=LY0Q5Rv4O3YC&pg=PA779 |chapter=Texas }}</ref>\n* 1970 \u2013 [[1970 United States Census#City rankings|Population]]: 393,476.<ref name=census1998 />\n* 1972 \u2013 [[Kimbell Art Museum]] opened.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n* 1973\n** [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort Worth Airport]] began operating.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n** [[Fort Worth Japanese Garden]] built.\n* 1975 \u2013 [[Fort Worth Water Gardens]] (fountain) built.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n* 1977 \u2013 Tarrant County Black Historical & Genealogical Society founded.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n* 1978\n** [[Sundance Square]] redevelopment began.<ref name=\"Kemp2004\">{{cite book|editor=Roger L. Kemp|title=Cities and the Arts: A Handbook for Renewal|chapter=Fort Worth|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=mNGG2g0Dl58C&pg=PA83|year=2004|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-2007-0|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/citiesartshandbo0000unse}}</ref>{{sfn|New York Times|2007}}\n** Fairmount Neighborhood Association incorporated.<ref name=FWL-archival />\n** [[Anne Valliant Burnett Tandy|Tandy]] Foundation established.<ref name=NonprofitExplorer /><ref name=handbook>{{citation |title=Handbook of Texas |publisher=Texas State Historical Association |title-link=Handbook of Texas }}</ref>\n* 1980 \u2013 [[1980 United States Census#City rankings|Population]]: 385,164.<ref name=census1998 />\n* 1981 \u2013 [[Billy Bob's Texas]] nightclub in business.{{sfn|New York Times|2007}}\n* 1982 \u2013 Tarrant Area Food Bank founded.<ref name=NonprofitExplorer>{{cite web |url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/search?c_code%5Bid%5D=&ntee%5Bid%5D=&order=revenue&q=fort+worth&sort_order=desc&state%5Bid%5D=TX&utf8=\u2713 |publisher=[[ProPublica]] |location=New York |title=Fort Worth, Texas |work=Nonprofit Explorer |editor=Mike Tigas and Sisi Wei |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n* 1983 \u2013 June 14: Hotel fire.<ref>{{citation |work=New York Times |title=5 are killed and 33 injured in hotel fire at Fort Worth |date=June 15, 1983 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/15/us/5-are-killed-and-33-injured-in-hotel-fire-at-fort-worth.html }}</ref>\n* 1990 \u2013 [[1990 United States Census#City rankings|Population]]: 447,619.<ref name=census1998>{{citation |title=Population of the 100 Largest Cities and Other Urban Places in the United States: 1790 to 1990 |year=1998 |url=https://www.census.gov/library/working-papers/1998/demo/POP-twps0027.html |publisher=US Census Bureau }}</ref>\n* 1991\n** AMC Sundance cinema in business.<ref name=FWL-facts />\n** [[Kay Granger]] became mayor.\n* 1992 \u2013 [[Tarrant County Courthouse|Courthouse]] shooting.<ref>{{citation |work=New York Times |title=Gunman Kills 2 Men and Injures 3 In Rampage at Texas Courthouse |date=July 2, 1992 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/07/02/us/gunman-kills-2-men-and-injures-3-in-rampage-at-texas-courthouse.html }}</ref>\n* 1994\n** US [[Naval Air Station Joint Reserve Base Fort Worth]] in operation.\n** [[National Cowgirl Museum and Hall of Fame]] relocated to city.\n* 1997 \u2013 Kay Granger became [[U.S. representative]] for [[Texas's 12th congressional district]].<ref name=GovTrack>{{cite web |url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members |title=Members of Congress |work=[[GovTrack.us|GovTrack]] |author=Civic Impulse, LLC |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=June 28, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Official Congressional Directory: 106th Congress |location=Washington DC |publisher=Government Printing Office |year=1999 |chapter=Texas |title-link=Official Congressional Directory |hdl=2027/uc1.l0083219832 }}</ref>\n* 1998 \u2013 City website online (approximate date).<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19981202214739/http://www.ci.fort-worth.tx.us/ |url=http://www.ci.fort-worth.tx.us/ |archivedate=December 1998 |title=City of Fort Worth Home Page |url-status=dead |via=Internet Archive, [[Wayback Machine]] }}</ref><!--Was there an earlier city website?-->{{Chronology citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n* 1999\n** September 15: Shooting at [[Larry Gene Ashbrook|Wedgwood Baptist Church]].<ref>{{citation |work=New York Times |title=Gunman Kills 7, and Himself, At Baptist Church in Fort Worth |date=September 16, 1999 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/09/16/us/gunman-kills-7-and-himself-at-baptist-church-in-fort-worth.html }}</ref>\n** [[Nancy Lee and Perry R. Bass Performance Hall|Bass Performance Hall]] opened.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n* 2000 \u2013 [[Trinity Railway Express]] (Dallas-Fort Worth) in operation.{{sfn|Roark|2003|ps=: \"Timeline\"}}\n\n==21st century==\n* 2001 \u2013 [[Fort Worth Central Station]] (known as the Fort Worth Intermodal Transportation Center until 2019) and [[Texas Cowboy Hall of Fame]] opened.\n* 2002 \u2013 [[LaGrave Field]] (stadium) and [[Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth|Modern Art Museum]] building opened.\n* 2010 \u2013 Population: 741,206 city; 6,371,773 [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth\u2013Arlington, TX MSA|metro]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov/dataviz/visualizations/026/508.php |year=2012 |title=Largest Urbanized Areas With Selected Cities and Metro Areas (2010) |publisher=US Census Bureau}}</ref> 19,728,244 [[Texas Triangle|megaregion]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.america2050.org/megaregions.html |title=Megaregions: Texas Triangle |accessdate=September 12, 2016 |publisher=[[Regional Plan Association]] |location=USA |work=America 2050}}</ref>\n* 2011 \u2013 May 14: [[Fort Worth mayoral election, 2011]] held; [[Betsy Price]] became mayor.\n* 2013 \u2013 [[Fort Worth Vaqueros FC]] (soccer club) formed.\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of Fort Worth, Texas]]\n* [[List of mayors of Fort Worth, Texas]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Tarrant County, Texas]]\n* {{req|Timeline of Texas}}\n* Timelines of other [[List of cities in Texas by population|cities]] in the [[North Texas]] area of Texas:<ref>{{cite web |publisher=[[North Central Texas Council of Governments]] |title=NCTCOG Members |location=Arlington |url=http://www.nctcog.org/edo/membership.asp |accessdate= April 7, 2017 }}</ref> [[Timeline of Arlington, Texas|Arlington]], [[Timeline of Dallas|Dallas]], [[Timeline of Denton, Texas|Denton]], [[Timeline of Garland, Texas|Garland]], [[Timeline of Irving, Texas|Irving]], [[Timeline of Plano, Texas|Plano]], [[Timeline of Wichita Falls, Texas|Wichita Falls]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title= History and Directory of Fort Worth ... Colored Businesses, Societies, Clubs, Churches, etc. |year=1907 |url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/009610546 |publisher=J.A. Hamilton }}\n* {{Citation \n|author = Federal Writers' Project \n|location=New York \n|publisher=Hastings House \n|series= [[American Guide Series]] \n|title=Texas: A Guide to the Lone Star State \n|year= 1940 \n|chapter=Fort Worth \n|via=HathiTrust \n| ref = {{harvid|Federal Writers' Project|1940}}\n|author-link=Federal Writers' Project \n|hdl=2027/mdp.39015002677667 \n}}\n* {{Citation \n|author = Texas Writers' Project |title=Research Data: Fort Worth and Tarrant County, Texas \n|year= 1941 \n|chapter=Chronology (draft) |volume=72 |chapter-url= http://fortworthtexasarchives.org/cdm/landingpage/collection/p16084coll1 |via =Fort Worth Library Digital Archive \n|author-link=Federal Writers' Project \n}}\n* {{cite book\n|author=Oliver Knight|title=Fort Worth: Outpost on the Trinity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KWUgwtMh6iUC|year=1953\n|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|isbn=978-0-87565-077-7}}\n* {{cite book|author=Robert Harris Talbert|title=Cowtown Metropolis: Case Study of a City's Growth and Structure|url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001264507 |year= 1956 |publisher=Leo Potishman Foundation, Texas Christian University |via=Hathi Trust\n| ref = {{harvid|Talbert|1956}}\n}} (fulltext)\n* {{cite book|editor=Richard M. Bernard and Bradley R. Rice|title=Sunbelt Cities: Politics and Growth since World War II |date=1983\n|publisher=Universi